Landscape_Type_Comments: Partial contour fort following the natural contours and which also appears to cut off a promontory, but sloping to the W. Located above the River Wye and Hereford to the E and the valley of the Worm Brook to the W, on the interfluve between the Rivers Wye and Severn catchments. Precipitous slopes to the W and N.
Univallate, contour hillfort located on summit of rounded hill at watershed of Whyle Brook and tributary and overlooking confluence, with River Lugg valley to W. Steep surrounding slopes.
Located part on slopes, part level ground. Sited on top slopes of a prominent hill above important confluences of the Rivers Wye and Lugg and Frome and Lugg
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Hilltop including the Adam's Rocks outcrop

Landscape_Type_Comments: The site is located on NW slopes just below the summit of a hill and, although it could be called a partial contour site, it is better referred to as a hillslope fort. Sited on a NW slope below the summit of a flat-topped steep hill pointing towards the confluence of the Rivers Teme, Clun and Leintwardine Fishery

One of the finest examples of a contour fort in the country. Located on the high ridge of the Malvern Hills above the River Severn valley on the E and River Leadon on the W. Its snaking ramparts encompass the Herefordshire Beacon itself and the S summit, called Millennium Hill.

The site is a cropmark but appears to cut off the promontory. Sited on a broad promontory overlooking the Monnow valley with steep slopes to the W, less so to the N and S. Highest point of the knoll or promontory is to the E which overlooks the hillfort.
The ramparts generally follow the contours at the top of a prominent spur. Sited on a steeply sloping spur directly overlooking and dominating a bend of the the River Wye. Slight slope to the S.

Partial contour hillfort, the site including the summit of the hill, but slopes to SW. Located within Chase Wood on a prominent hill above Ross-on-Wye with steep surrounding slopes apart from on S side.
Contour hillfort on spur summit. Overlooks the River Wye on a prominent spur near its confluence with the River Lugg.
Complex contour fort on prominent hill. Sited above steep slopes on prominent hill top, now tree covered, above the River Teme and its confluence with the River Clun and Leintwardine Fishery.
Large contour hillfort. Located on steep and prominent hill within Credenhill Park Wood dominating a major bend in the River Wye.
The fort partly follows the contours. Sited on a spur above a significant bend of the River Lugg dominating the Leintwardine Fishery.
Important contour hillfort located on the summit of Dinedor Hill overlooking the River Wye and Hereford and its confluence with the River Lugg and the confluence of the Lugg and Frome.
The location of the site is not exact. Located on NE spur slopes on a bend of the River Lugg.
Sloping spur promontory.Located on steep slopes of a spur just below the summit of Dorstone Hill overlooking the River Dore.
Univallate, cliff-edge, inland promontory fort. Located on wooded NE-facing slope at the edge of S-facing limestone cliffs above the River Teme.
Unusual inland promontory hillfort located directly adjacent to the River Wye at stream confluence.
Unusual location on flat plateau top suggests level terrain fort. Located at the top plateau edge of a gentle rise above a stream valley which eventually meets the River Wye to the S.
A (former) hillslope enclosure. Located on steep slopes overlooking the Kyre Brook and the headwaters of the River Frome to the S and W.
Site generally follows the contours on ridge top. Isolated wooded site located on a hill above the River Leadon.
Ramparts closely follow the contours apart from N half of east side. Located on a hill overlooking the W bank of the River Arrow and near the confluence of the Rivers Lugg and Arrow.
The site generally follows the contours of the spur. Large, very prominent and now wooded multivallate hillfort located on a spur promontory on major bends of the River Wye at Symonds Yat.

The three hillforts of Mere Hill, Pyon Wood (Atlas No 0029) and Croft Ambrey (Atlas No 0012)  are located in a line along the River Lugg. Mere Hill located at the edge of steep escarpment overlooking valley of River Lugg in vicinity of Pyon Wood and Croft Ambrey.

Partial contour hillfort. Steep slopes are a feature of the site. Because of the topographic nature of the site on two hills, the aspect is very variable. Located on two hills, Midsummer Hill and Hollybush Hill on the ridge of the Malvern Hills. Aspect variable about the large site, predominately NW.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: The two hilltops of Midsummer Hill to the north and Hollybush Hill to the south with intervening valley.

Landscape_Type_Comments: Site generally follows the contours. Located on the plateau top of Ridge Hill on the interfluve of the Rivers Severn and Wye.

Main_Display_Name: Pen-Twyn Camp, Brilley, Herefordshire (Pen Twyn Camp)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Hill top site follows the contours. Isolated and prominent site overlooking the River Wye above Hay-on-Wye.
Large, level terrain, triple banked and ditched enclosure, showing mostly as cropmark in arable field and located on an elevated level plateau at E end of a ridge overlooking the Monnow Valley to S.

Main_Display_Name: Poston Camp, Herefordshire (Lower Park Wood Camp)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Inland promontory fort, the single massive rampart cutting off the promontory spur and sited above the River Dore in the Golden Valley.
Site roughly follows the contours. Located on a prominent spur below Croft Ambrey, above a very significant bend of the River Lugg.
Site follows the contours. Located at the confluence of Holly and Humber Brooks.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Interesting location on the edge of Holly Brook on small flat-topped knoll, possibly artificially levelled.

Landscape_Type_Comments: The elongated E to W, site follows the 100m contour to the E dipping to the W at the W end. Located on a low, but prominent, hill overlooking the River Lugg.
The site roughly follows the contours of the spur. Located in Timberline Wood on a significant SE spur above the River Dore and Golden Valley on the SW and the River Wye on the NW.
Hillslope fort sited on slopes above the Humber Brook and River Lugg on a prominent E-W ridge.

Main_Display_Name: Wall Hills Camp, Ledbury, Herefordshire (Wall Hills, Ledbury)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Isolated, large, partial contour fort, with two enclosures, that to the S c. 6m higher than that to the N and located on a knoll overlooking the upper reaches of the River Leadon and the valley of Preston Brook to the W.
Site follows the contours on hill summit. Large site on hill summit overlooking the Kyre Brook to the N and W and the headwaters of the River Frome to the S and W.
Site roughly follows the contours in a circle. Prominent site at the confluence of the Rivers Honddu and Monnow
Site roughly follows the contours. Large isolated hillfort located on the wooded summit of Wapley Hill.
Hillslope fort located on spur end overlooking a stream above Holly Brook, a tributary of the River Lugg.

Fort destroyed by quarrying and mining. Formerly the site probably followed the contours. Formerly on one of the three summits of the Clees (Abdon, Brown and Titterstone) that dominate SE Shropshire. High, steep and prominent Abdon Burf overlooked the valleys of the River Corve to the W and the River Rea/Rea Brooks to the E.

Located on hill top above the River Onny and valleys to the N where the Onny valley opens out into the lower lying valley of the Camlad/Onny headwaters. Also at the confluence of the East and West Onny's in an area of prominent hillforts.
Steeply sloping hillside site between 210-225 m O.D. Sited on a cliff edge to the N of Llanymynech Hill.

Classified as a promontory fort by the VCH (1908). However, it does not just cut off the promontory but has earthworks around all sides of the circuit, roughly following the contours. Sited on the SE end of a steep-sided spur summit  above the River Unk at a stream confluence.
Good example of an inland promontory fort. Located on the promontory summit of Bodbury Hill, with precipitous slopes above the Cardingmill Valley and access into the Long Mynd.
Possible hillslope fort located on the NE slopes of Bulthy Hill to the NW of Middletown Hill and one of the five hillforts of the Breidden Hills sited above the River Severn.
Site follows the contours. Occupying one of the highest points in the former medieval Mogg Forest, but on a low hill.
Undulating site generally following the contours. Located on the summit of Burrow Hill near to the confluence of the Rivers Clun and Kemp, in an area of clusters of prominent hillforts.

Interior slopes gently to the SW corner. Sited on Sunnyhill above the valley of the River Clun to the S, the valley of the River Kemp to the N and  the confluence of the Rivers Clun and Unk to the SW.
Situated on a sandstone ridge, with wooded slopes overlooking the plain of the River Roden.

Main_Display_Name: Caer Caradoc, Clun, Shropshire (Caer Caradoc, Chapel Lawn; Gaer Ditches)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Very good example of a partial contour fort, being tilted towards the valley of the River Redlake to the NE. Superbly sited on a spur overlooking the River Redlake with the Rivers Clun to the N and Teme to the S.
High, prominent and craggy partial contour fort, some 380m long, and falling 30m from N to S and located on the steep ridge of Caer Caradoc Hill.
Probably the best defined promontory fort in Shropshire. Located on E-facing slopes of a N to S ridge of a very steep promontory above a sharp bend of the River Camlad.
Contour hillfort located on prominent hill above Folly Brook and above its confluence with the River Clun.
Partial contour fort sited on a very steep wooded spur some 100m above a bend of the River Camlad and opposite to Caerbre.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: A very steep wooded spur some 100m above a bend of the River Camlad.

Landscape_Type_Comments: The ramparts follow the contours. A small multivallate fort, roughly triangular in plan, located on the isolated Callow Hill overlooking the Rea Brook to the north and one of several sites below the dominent Earl's Hill fort surmounting Pontesford Hill.
Hillslope fort sited on SE slopes of Castle Idris. Located on a shelf of steep E-facing slopes of Castle Idris hill at the confluence of Folly Brook and the River Clun.

Main_Display_Name: Castle Ring, Gorsty Bank, Shropshire (Gorsty Bank)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Site follows the contours. Sited on a knoll on the interfluve overlooking the confluence of the River Camlad and Aylesford Brook and valley of the Rea Brook to the NE and Hope Valley to the E

Inland promontory fort, Castle Ring often referred to as defended Iron Age farmstead, but, despite it small size, occupies strong defensive position, with substantial defences on marked Ridgeway Hill above, and SW of, bend of River Onny at the edge of Plowden Woods and in an area of prominent hillforts.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Marked promontory above the River Onny.

Main_Display_Name: Castle Hill, Oak Hill, Shropshire (Oak Hill)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Although the S side has the promontory cut off by a rampart, steep natural defences on W and N have artificial strengthening, therefore site classified as contour hillfort. Located on high steep site spur at N end of Stiperstones looking across the valley of Rea Brook towards Severn valley.
Site generally follows the contours. Situated at the junction of a W and S spur, at the SW end of Stitt Hill,
Fort follows the contours tof hill to its defensive advantage. Set on a prominent hill at the SE end of Long Mountain, overlooking the Rea Brook to the S and E and undulating lowlands to N.

The rampart follows the contours. Located on a small, domed land ow hill summit above and overlooking the narrow valley of Ledwyche Brook to the W and Caynham Brook to the N, and near to the confluence of the Rivers Teme and Corve at Ludlow.
Contour hillfort sited within a steep-sided bend at the confluence of Stratford Brook and another stream, tributaries of the River Worfe.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Steep-sided spur on bend at the confluence of Stratford Brook and another stream,

Landscape_Type_Comments: Possible contour fort but as most of site destroyed this cannot be certain. High and prominent on the rounded summit of Brown Clee Hill, Clee Burf occupies a very prominent location and overlooks the valleys of the River Corve to the W and the River Rea/Rea Brooks to the E.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Rounded summit of Brown Clee Hill.

Landscape_Type_Comments: Contour fort following the contours of a steep isolated hill. Located on steep wooded slopes of an isolated rocky ridge/hill above the Afon Cynllaith watercourse.
A hillslope enclosure on moderate slopes. Sited at the end of a N-S spur above Cwm Colstey with moderate slopes on the E and W and gradual on the N and S.

Partial contour hillfort occupies prominent hill top and associated ridge, crowning the steep summit and S slopes of Pontesford Hill with far-reaching views commanding the valleys of the Rea and Cound Brooks.
A lowland hillfort which follows the contours on a small knoll. Low-lying site on a slight knoll with the River Severn to the SW and the River Roden to the NE.

Site generally follows the contours. Located on steep slopes, in a situation of great strength, on a knoll at the end of an elevated spur opposite to Castle Idris fort at Newcastle on Clun, and at the confluence of Folly Brook and the River Clun, in an area of small hillforts at the extreme point of the Clun Forest hills.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Knoll at the end of an elevated spur.

Main_Display_Name: Haughmond Hill Camp, Shropshire (Haughmond Castle; Castle Earthwork)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Site generally follows the contours. Sited near to the top of Haughmond Hill at the W end of the escarpment and overlooking a sharp bend of the River Severn. Extensive views of the Severn Valley and North Shropshire Plain.
Possible, partial contour site located on a slight rise or knoll above Corn Brook, a stream tributary of the River Teme, and to the S of Clee Hill.

Very large contour hillfort, at c. 57ha one of the largest in Britain. Straddles the England /Wales border where the Afon Vyrnwy, Tanat and Cain reach the Severn plain. Sides steep so little defence needed.
Partial contour fort sloping slightly from E to W. Sited on a spur top on the lower W slopes of Brown Clee Hill overlooking the valley of the River Corve.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Spur top on lower W slopes.

Landscape_Type_Comments: Partial contour fort with gentle E-facing slopes and summit of hill located above the River Onny.
Fine contour fort located on a glacial knoll overlooking the North Shropshire Plain to the N and E.

Site covers N summit of the hill on ground rising to the NW and and isolated knoll to the E. Located on the N summit of the prominent Nesscliffe Hill rising above the Shropshire Plain and River Severn to the SW and River Perry to the NE.
Generally undulating ground conditions. Located on undulating ground near Pave Lane village and next to a pronounced glacial gully and adjacent bank, also of glacial origin.
Site slightly slopes to the NE, partially following the contours. Located on a col on the lower NE facing spur slopes of Pontesford Hill below Earl's Hill hillfort.
Site appears to follow the contours. Small steep wooded site above the River Clun.

Main_Display_Name: Ratlinghope Hill Camp, Shropshire (Ratlinghope Hill; Stitt Hill)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Site generally follows the contours. A cross bank and ditch with scarping elsewhere, encloses a spur on Ratinghope Hill.
Hillslope fort on Wentnor Prolley Moor overlooking Criftin Brook and above the River East Onny on the edge of a plateau at the foot of the Long Mynd. Slopes gently to the S and SW.

Site makes full use of the natural topography. Located on the lower of the two summits of the wooded Roveries and commanding the headwaters of the Camlad-Onny valley and the Lydham Pass, to the SW of the Long Mynd.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Rocky summit of the W Roveries hill.

Landscape_Type_Comments: Site makes full use of the natural topography. Located on the higher of the two summits of the wooded Roveries, strategically sited above the headwaters of the Rivers Camlad and Onny and the Lydham Pass, to the SW of the Long Mynd.

Definite and unique marsh fort, in being located on two glacial mounds. Isolated marsh fort, comprising two enclosures located on gravel glacial mounds, formerly surrounded by wetland and fen near to the River Perry and located near to the present Berth Pool.

Main_Display_Name: The Burgs, Shropshire (The Buries; Bayston Hill)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Located on a low-lying knoll overlooking the Severn plain and the confluence of the Severn and Rea Brook.

Main_Display_Name: The Ditches, Mogg Forest, Shropshire (Larden Ditches; Mogg Ditches; The Rings; Wynbury Castle; Larden Castle)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Located on an interfluve position between the valley of the River Corve and brooks. Interior gently domed.
Small inland promontory fort on gentle SE facing slope. Cuts off a small sloping spur on gentle SE facing slopes between two dingles above the River Unk and with commanding views to the S and SE.
Type estimated. The site makes use of the natural slopes of the hill. Located on the narrow steep razor-edge ridge of The Lawley below the summit of the hill and the upper site.

The exact type of hillfort (if indeed one) cannot be exactly defined and partial contour site only estimated, though site makes full use of the topography. Located on the very exposed sharp ridge of The Lawley, the very distinctive razor-edged hill next (NE) to Caer Caradoc and surrounded by precipitous slopes on all sides.
Both the inner and outer enclosures follow the contours with slopes in all directions. Steep hogsback ridge located above the River Severn on the S and River Tern to the N.

Site slopes in most directions, but follows the contours. Located on the summit of Titterstone Clee, one of the Clee hills (with Brown), that dominate SE Shropshire overlooking the River Teme and lower lying valleys to the W and Ledwyche Brook and River Rea to the E.

Main_Display_Name: Wall Camp, Kynnersley, Shropshire (The Wall; Kinnersley Wall)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Important and large (12ha), isolated and flat lowland marsh fort located on Tibberton Moor near to the confluence of the River Strine and River Tern and River Meese and Tern.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Low lying sandstone and Boulder Clay former island in the midst of former fen.

Landscape_Type_Comments: Interior slopes from N to S. Sited on a the S end of an isolated knoll/ spur overlooking the valley of the Rea Brook to S and SW and Rowley Brook and uplands beyond..
Small contour hillfort located on summit of Wart Hill on steep slopes above the River Onny opposite to Burrow Camp and the confluence of the Onny with Quinny and Byne Brooks.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Hill top summit of Wart Hill.

Landscape_Type_Comments: Univallate contour fort lying at 155m OD on plateau gravels and Bagshot sands.  It occupies the highest point in a triangle of plateaus which lie between the Thames, the Kennet and the Berkshire Downs.  Higher in the N, sloping in the SW towards Bucklebury Common.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Narrow arc-shaped ridge lying to the W and S of the River Pang

Main_Display_Name: Bussock Camp, West Berkshire (Bussock Wood Camp)
Landscape_Type_Comments: A contour fort, univallate in the W and bivallate elsewhere lying on a ridge at 145m OD
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Situated at the end of a gravelly ridge which has a steep natural slope to the N and W.

Landscape_Type_Comments: A univallate contour hiilfort lying on Cretaceous Upper Chalk overlain by calcareous silty soils of the Andover 1 series. The hillfort lies at 295m OD on the highest point on the chalk in Britain. The hillforts of Fosbury, Beacon Hill and Ladle Hill can be seen. Farther afield, both Danebury and Quarley Hill are visible to the S.  Under optimum conditions Uffington Castle, Rams Hill and Segsbury can be made out on the northern horizon
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Situated at the widening of an EW chalk ridge with extensive views in all directions

Landscape_Type_Comments: A possible former contour fort lying at approximately 149m OD. The northern side survives as two parallel banks in adjacent woodland which follow the contours of a steep slope for several metres (verified by the West Berkshire HER officer in 2011)
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Lies in a strong defensive position on a ridge of high ground.

Landscape_Type_Comments: Large, oval, contour hillfort located at the SW corner of small downland plateau at 206m OD with the River Kennet to the SW and Ermin Street to the NE. Steep slopes to S and W and flat plateau to N and E.
A contour fort situated at 242m OD on a steep, N-facing scarp edge
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Steep N-facing scarp edge on Eston Nab

Landscape_Type_Comments: A contour fort lying at 137m OD on an E-facing spur overlooking the upper reaches of the River Pang. Wood & Hardy (1962: 53) noted that its position overlooked two early routeways. The first leading to the Pang Valley-Churn gap which breaches the main escarpment of the Downs towards the Vale of the White Horse, and the 'West Ridgeway' which runs between the Thames crossings near Streatley and the Kennet crossing near Newbury.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: On the E-facing side of a spur

Landscape_Type_Comments: A univallate hillfort at 120m OD which closely follows the 120m contour of a northward projecting spur and its small valleys.

A contour fort situated in a strong defensive position at 220m OD on the summit of Allen Knott. From the summit, Lake Windermere, the peaks of Gummers How and Orrest Head, the Langdale Pikes, Crinkle Crags, the Old Man of Coniston and the hills surrounding the Kirkstone Pass are visible.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: On the summit of Allen Knott

Landscape_Type_Comments: A univallate hillslope fort lying at 183m OD on the upper slopes of Barrock Fell.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Situated on the upper slopes of Barrock Fell.

Main_Display_Name: Humbledon Hill, Tyne and Wear (Homeldon; Hamdon; Hamylden; Hamildon; Humbledon Bank)
Landscape_Type_Comments: A two-phase contour fort lying at 91m OD on the summit of Humbledon Hill.

A partial contour fort located on an irregular E-W double summit ridge of Carrock Fell at approximately 640m OD. The highest part of the enclosure is a rocky knoll lying at the western end, descending gradually eastwards in a series of steps beyond which it rises again to a smooth rounded knoll in the east.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: EW summit ridge of Carrock Fell

Landscape_Type_Comments: Sited on an inland promontory on Castle Crag at 366m OD, a projection of rock extending NE from Birks Crag which is precipitous on three sides. On the fourth side in the SW it was enclosed by a stone rampart and two deep ditches.
A univallate contour fort situated at 305m OD on the relatively flat summit of Castle Crag
A multivallate contour fort lying at 90m OD on the summit of Castle How
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Summit of a rocky knoll with steep sides in the N and S

Landscape_Type_Comments: Multiple enclosure fort of concentric rock-cut ditches in the E and W at 170m OD.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Rocky knoll at its highest point

Landscape_Type_Comments: Contour fort lying at 182m OD on the summit of a hill known as The Helm.  Possibly once completely enclosed.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Summit of a ridge known as 'The Helm'

Landscape_Type_Comments: Contour fort lying at 182m OD on the summit of a slight knoll within Yanwath Wood
A multiple enclosure hillfort located on a rocky knoll or promontory at 396m OD
A purported inland promontory fort on a natural rocky outcrop at 16m OD
Promontory fort situated at 68m on a precipitous promontory above the River Wear
A contour fort on the summit of a low, flat topped hill at 95m OD. From the summit there are extensive views in most directions expect in the SE where it is overlooked by Birkrigg Common.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Summit of a low flat-topped hill

Landscape_Type_Comments: A triple ditched enclosure lying at 31m OD on the summit and SE slope of Swarthy Hill on a large outcropping of Devensian Till and Sand, overlooking Allonby Bay
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: On the summit and SE slope of Swarthy Hill

Landscape_Type_Comments: A multivallate contour fort sited on a prominent limestone ridge at 183m OD
A possible contour fort located on the summit of a high ridge within woodland at 160m OD
A multivallate contour fort on the summit of Dunmallard Hill at 240m OD
A univallate contour fort lying in a commanding position at 324m OD on the western edge of the summit on Scarside Common.

Main_Display_Name: Kemp's Walk, Meikle Larbrax, Dumfries & Galloway (Kemp's Wark)
Landscape_Type_Comments: A large promontory on the coastal escarpment overlooking the beach in Larbrax Bay

Main_Display_Name: Dunskey Golf Course, Dumfries & Galloway (Portpatrick Post Office Radio Station; Fort Cottage)

Landscape_Type_Comments: A univallate contour fort situated at 214m OD on the summit of a hill with good visibility in all directions.
Coastal promontory immediately NW of sea inlet of Portobello.
Much faulted coastal headland with sea inlets to N and S.

Cassington Ring, Oxfordshire (Cassington Mill Big Ring)

Landscape_Topography_Comments: Follows the contours of an isolated hill

Parallels with Casterley Camp and Alfred's Castle (Brown et al 2005, 159).

Main_Display_Name: Tregeare Rounds Camp, Cornwall (Dameliock Castle; Tregaer Rounds)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Multiple enclosure hillslope hillfort, of concentric form, sited on gentle NW-facing upper slope of prominent ridge overlooking the valley of a tributary to the River Allen.

Multivallate multiple enclosure fort and annexe, sited on steep W-facing slope near and above Gerrans Bay, SW Veryan. Very steep surrounding slopes to stream valley on W and NW, steep to S and moderate to E.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located on a steep hill, steep to the west with a level interior

Landscape_Type_Comments: Large, multiple enclosure, hillslope hillfort sited on NE-facing slope of prominent upland ridge at heads of two tributaries of River Ottery which surrounds the site at a distance to N, E, W. Steep surrounding slopes to N, E less so on W, the SE side above a steep stream valley.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Sited on a commanding high spur overlooking the Ottery valley

Landscape_Type_Comments: Small contour fort situated in a commanding position on summit of steep and prominent Trencrom Hill on Lelant Downs.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located on the level summit of a hill

Landscape_Type_Comments: Multivallate promontory fort (aka cliff castle) sited on commanding rocky headland dividing St Austell and Mevagissey Bays. Substantial sea cliffs to the E, S and W.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Sea cliff headland site inaccessible from the sea

Landscape_Type_Comments: Promontory fort (aka cliff castle) sited on imposing, sloping, narrow and rocky, SW-facing granite coastal headland, c. 100m wide but reducing and c. 200m long, on promontory dividing Mill Bay or Nanizal and bay seaward of Higher Boristow Cliff, St Leven.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located on a steep and narrow granite headland with good views of Nanjizal Bay

Landscape_Type_Comments: Irregularly shaped promontory fort (aka cliff castle) situated on a rocky NW-facing headland between Halldrine and Porthmoina Coves, Zennor. Steep natural sea cliffs on all sides except landward SE quadrant, Steep natural sea cliffs on all sides except landward SE quadrant.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Headland site above the sea

Landscape_Type_Comments: Promontory fort (aka cliff castle) sited on rocky SE-facing coastal headland of Chynhalls Point separating Coverack Bay to NE and Porthbeer Bay to SW.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Coastal headland site with sea cliffs

Landscape_Type_Comments: Part of much eroded promontory fort (aka cliff castle) sited on edge of prominent NNW-facing sloping coastal cliff known as Carvannel Downs, overlooking Basset's Cove, Illogan.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Coastal headland location with sea cliffs

Main_Display_Name: Dodman Castle, Cornwall (Dodman Point; The Dodman)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Large promontory fort (aka cliff castle) sited on Dodman Point, prominent flat-topped headland projecting S into the English Channel, SW of Gorran Haven.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Coastal headland location and sea cliffs

Landscape_Type_Comments: Promontory fort (aka cliff castle) located on Griffin's Point, a headland promontory projecting W into the Atlantic N of Watergate Bay. On S cliffs high, exposed, and precipitous. Stream valley almost surrounds landward E side. Steep descent to landward NE side.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Coastal headland location and sea cliffs

Main_Display_Name: Lankidden, Cornwall (Carrack; Carrick Luz Fort; The Castle; Arrowan)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Univallate promontory fort (aka cliff castle) situated on coastal headland of Linkidden, jutting S into Atlantic, and which terminates to S in the rocks of Carrick Luz.  Steep sea cliffs to E, S, W.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Coastal headland and sea cliffs

Main_Display_Name: Little Dennis, Cornwall (Dennis Head; Little Dinas)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Part of site of promontory fort (aka cliff castle) of c. 8.7ha located on NE part of E-facing Dennis Head headland on S shore of Helford River estuary, with Gillan Creek to S.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Coastal headland and sea cliffs

Landscape_Type_Comments: Excavated promontory fort (aka cliff castle) sited on small W-facing headland overlooking Gamper Bay at Mayon Cliff and overlooking Castle Zawn cove to N. Steep sea cliffs on N and W, S side boulder strewn slope drops steeply to stream.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Coastal headland and sea cliffs of north-west facing promontory with sea cliffs to west nd north and south to steep rocky stream

Landscape_Type_Comments: Much eroded univallate promontory fort (aka cliff castle) sited on the SW-NW-facing headland of Park Head jutting out into Atlantic. Sea cliffs to N, S, W.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Coastal headland and sea cliffs

Landscape_Type_Comments: Promontory fort (aka cliff castle) on NW-facing headland of Penhale Point, which juts out from coastline dividing Holywell Bay to the N from Perran Bay to S, with commanding views in all directions. Sheer sea cliffs on seaward side.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Coastal headland and sea cliffs location running from a small cove to the south to a steep slope on the norh-east

Landscape_Type_Comments: Promontory fort (aka cliff castle) located on tip of  SSW-facing rocky headland of Rame Head, which divides Cawsand Bay from Whitsand Bay, forming protective natural barrier on the W side of Plymouth Sound. Steep sea cliffs on all but NE side where narrow neck of land connects site to mainland,
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Bank cuts off the coastal headland at Rame Head bounded by sea cliffs

Landscape_Type_Comments: Bivallate and much eroded promontory fort (aka cliff castle) located on promontory projecting W into the Atlantic N of Mawgan Porth. Level and moderately sloping interior with high sea cliffs with a narrow ridge projecting seaward below.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Coastal headland location with sea cliffs

Landscape_Type_Comments: Much eroded promontory fort (aka cliff castle) sited on Rosemullion Head jutting ESE into Atlantic.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Coastal headland location with sea cliffs

Landscape_Type_Comments: Multiple enclosure promontory fort located on promontory at tidal confluence of Cowlands Creek, Lamouth Creek and River Fal, Feock.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Coastal headland location with sea cliffs

Main_Display_Name: The Rumps, Cornwall (Rumps Point; Pentire Fort)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Promontory fort (aka cliff castle) located on rocky N-facing coastal headland of Rumps Point, between Padstow and Port Quin Bays. Steep sea cliffs to N, E, W.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Coastal headland location with sea cliffs

Main_Display_Name: Trereen Dinas, Cornwall (Gurnard's Head; Gurnards Head)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Excavated promontory fort (aka cliff castle) cutting off the N-facing Gurnard's Head at its narrowest point making much use of natural stone outcrops. Steep sea cliffs to all but S side.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Coastal headland location with sea cliffs

Landscape_Type_Comments: Fine promontory fort (aka cliff castle) on WNW-facing headland protecting the beaching cove of St Columb Porth (Porth Beach) to S and Whipsiderry Beach to N and between Newquay and Watergate Bays at Newquay.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Sloping coastal east-west headland location with sea cliffs and protecting the beaching cove of St Columb Porth on the south

Landscape_Type_Comments: Promontory fort (aka cliff castle) sited on a small rocky granite S-facing headland known as Treryn which has flat summit and slopes steeply to sea on E, S, and W. Polry and Barcastle Coves to W and Cripp's Cove to E cut into headland.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located on a south facing rocky promontory with fairly flat grassy summit sloping to the sea on three sides

Landscape_Type_Comments: Small promontory fort (aka cliff castle) sited on eroded coastal promontory. Located along exposed coastline facing the Atlantic, but overlooked by steeply sloping ground to E. Defined by steep natural rock sea cliffs on all sides but E,
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located on a small promontory in exposed position

Main_Display_Name: Winecove Point Complex, Cornwall (Wine Cove Point)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Complex promontory fort (aka cliff castle) sited on three W-facing promontories S of Treyarnon Bay, its nature either the result of sea erosion of a large single site, or initial construction as possibly three enclosures.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located on three promontories

Landscape_Type_Comments: Small, univallate, hillslope hillfort sited in prominent location on slight slope on NE shoulder of ridge W of St Newlyn East. Steep surrounding slopes to N, NE, moderate to SE, moderate to level on W.

Main_Display_Name: Willapark, Boscastle, Cornwall (Willapark Camp, Willapark, Forrabury and Minster)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Large promontory fort (aka cliff castle) on prominant W-facing coastal headland just S of Boscatle Harbour and Eastern Blackapit inlet and just N of Western Blackapit inlet. S of Penally Point and W of Forrabury Common.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located on an undulating coastal slope

Landscape_Type_Comments: The hillfort comprises three, somewhat concentric enclosing elements. They surround the domed summit of a low-rise hilltop at 74m OD.
The promontory is rectangular in shape, projecting E into Glandore Harbour with a single bank and ditch located on the W side. It is situated at an elevation of 10m OD.

Main_Display_Name: Caherconree, Kerry (Ballyarkane Oughter, Beheenagh, Gortaleen Mountain)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Triangular shaped inland promontory on the WSW facing slope of Caherconree Mountain. Ramparts protect the E approach to the site. The remainder of the hillfort is formed by cliff-face to the N, S and W. Excellent views from the summit.

An oval shaped hillfort following the contours of the hilltop is located on the E spur of the Nagle Mountains. It surrounds domed summit and offers panoramic views in all directions. The entrance is positioned on the most accessible approach at the WNW, where the slope is gradual and less sever. Carn Tighernagh overlooks the Blackwater and Bride river valleys to the east and north.
Positioned at the summit of a partial spur on an E - W running ridge. The majority of the hillfort is positioned on level terrain. The southern section slopes severly to the south.

Contour fort in commanding position, surrounding the summit of a prominent hill and overlooking the Blackwater and Fushion river valleys to the N and S. The site offers panoramic views in all directions.

Contour fort following the natural contours of the hill, positioned at the flat summit of Claragh Mountain at 452 OD. The mountain forms a distinct topographical feature in the landscape. The summit offers panoramic views in all directions.

Main_Display_Name: Faha, Kerry (Begagh; Binn na Port; An Fhaiche)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Large, bivallate inland promontory fort on E _ W running ridge, positioned on E side of Brandon Mountain in the Dingle Peninsula. The triangular promontory narrows to the W and is bounded on the N and S by steep cliffs. The remains of two widely spaced stone walls cut off the E, most accessible side of the promontory. There are panoramic views of Dingle Bay to the S and Tralee Bay to the N. Mount Brandon blocks views to the W. The ridge Faha hillfort is positioned on blends into the mountainous terrain and is hard to distinguish from a distance.

Glanbane hillfort in commanding position on the last high point at the E edge of the Sliabh Mish Mountains, overlooking the valley of the River Lee and River Maine to the N, E and S. It follows the contours of the hill on the N and E. The S and W sections of the hillfort are situated on flat terrain. Panoramic views from the summit.
Situated on the summit of a low hill to the immediate W of Tralee town. Although only at 30m OD, the site affords panoramic views, with particular emphasis on views of Tralee Bay.
The hillfort surrounds the summit of Dunmurry Hill. The majority of the monument occupies the SE facing slopes of the hilltop. Panoramic views from the summit.

The hillfort surrounds the domed summit of Carrigeen Hill, with extensive views in all directions. It generally follows the contours of the hill, creating an oval shape in plan. Hughstown hillfort forms one of nine possible hillforts within the Baltinglass cluster.

Large, multivallate hillfort surrounding the domed summit and W slopes of Kill Hill. The site is situated at the NE foothills of the Wicklow Mountains and overlooks the town of Naas to the SW, with panoramic views in all directions.
Hillslope fort positioned on severe SW facing slopes of Brandon Hill and overlooking the source of the Ciodiagh River.

In commanding position surrounding the flat summit of Mount Garret. Circular level terrain fort has panoramic views in all directions, however, the shape of the hill prevents views of the N base of the mountain. The mountain overlooks an E - W running gap in the Slieveardagh Hills.

Positioned surrounding the summit of a hill-ridge. The hillfort is draped over either side of a narrow N - S running ridge, with the E and W section of the enclosing elements disregarding the contours of the hill in order to attain a circular plan.

Partial contour fort surrounding the low-domed summit of Freestone Hill, following the 130m contour at the E, S and W. The hilltop is located at the S foothills of the Castlecomer Hills, overlooking Kilkenny town and a N - S running natural routeway through a gap in the Slieveardagh Hills and Castlecomer Hills.

Contour fort enclosing the flat summit of Ballinkillin Hill. The hillfort is positioned on the southern summit in a N - S running ridge of broad hills. The Barrow River is highly visible to the W and SW.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Hill summit and ridge of hills.

Landscape_Type_Comments: Widely spaced multiple enclosure in commanding position surrounding the somewhat flat summit of Ballylin Hill. The hilltop acts as a small spur in the N - S running escarpment, N of the Mullaghareirk Mountains. This provides Ballylin Hill with exceptional views of the Limerick plains to the N, E and S.

Main_Display_Name: Castle Gale, Limerick (Carrig Henry, Darragh More, 'The Citadel')
Landscape_Type_Comments: Inland promontory fort positioned on the Cork/Limerick border in the Ballyhoura Hills. Situated on the summit of Carrig Henry, a natural promontory protected at the N, E and W by cliff face and to the S by two closely spaced banks of stone. Extensive views of the Limerick plains to the N and the Blackwater valley to the S.
Contour fort positioned on the low-domed summit of an isolated hill, 7.5km S of Limerick City. Panoramic views from the summit.

Contour fort positioned on the low-domed hill shoulder of an isolated hill, 7.5km S of Limerick City. There are extensive views to the N, E and S. Views to the W are blocked by the summit of Friarstown Hill.

Multiple enclosure surrounding the summit of isolated hill in low-lying terrain. Panoramic views in all directions. Hillfort is overlooking the Loobagh River to 200m to the S. Enclosing elements follow the natural countours of the hill.
Circular multiple enclosure on summit of low, dome shaped hill. This hilltop dominates the surrounding flat, low-lying terrain. The summit offers panoramic views of the surrounding landscape.
Multiple enclosure on summit of isolated hill in low-lying terrain. Summit is domed and offers panoramic views in all directions.
Hillfort closely following the contours, positioned on the commanding and isolated  Tory Hill, overlooking low-lying terrain in all directions.
Surrounds low-domed summit of prominent hill, overlooking Granard town to the NE and River Rhine to S.
Multiple enclosure on S shoulder of level hilltop, surrounding low summit and overlooking Black River to E. Panoramic views from summit.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Large flat summit of low-lying hill.

Landscape_Type_Comments: Multiple enclosure positioned surrounding the summit of a low, conical hill overlooking the River Blackwater, which feeds the larger River Boyne. The hillfort follows the 120m contour at the N and partially at the E and W.
Contour fort surrounding domed summit of Drumran Hill. In commanding position overlooking a tributary of the Garra River to N and W.
Hillslope fort positioned surrounding southern summit of ridge of hills, with excellent views to E, S and W. Overlooking Devlin River and its tributaries. This river system feeds the Boyne River.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: South facing hill summit, as S edge of ridge of hills.

Landscape_Type_Comments: Multiple enclosure positioned in upland terrain on gently sloping W facing hillslope, overlooking Fuarawn River to W and S. Excellent views to N, S and W.

Contour fort in commanding position surrounding summit of a steep hilltop, at E edge of Slieve Bloom Mountains. Site overlooks a number of tributary rivers feeding the Camcor River. Cumber Lower hillfort 1.9km to NE.

Main_Display_Name: Cumber Lower, Offaly (Knocknaman Hill, Cumber Upper, Forelacka, Lismoney)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Multiple enclosure in commanding position surrounding summit of a steep hilltop, at E edge of Slieve Bloom Mountains. Site overlooks Camcor River to N. Ballymacmurragh hillfort 1.9km to SW.
A possible inland promontory fort lying at 277m OD
A possible inland promontory fort lying at approximately 64m OD. General area appears relatively level
Possibly promontory fort lying at 328m OD on a north-westerly spur on the Uldale Fells.
Contour fort surrounding domed summit and NW facing slopes of Mewlaghadooey Hill. Panoramic views from the summit. Overlooking Francis River and its tributaries to NW.

Multiple enclosure following contours on summit of flat hilltop. Panoramic views from summit. SW section of hillfort at edge of steeper incline falling into SW - NE running valley. Excellent views of this valley from hillfort.
Contour fort positioned at the flat summit of an isolated hill, with panoramic views of the surrounding low-land terrain from the summit.
Contour fort at summit of a broad, low hill in low lying terrain. Extensive views to the N and W.
Contour fort at summit of hilltop at NE edge of steep slope, overlooking Sligo coastline with panoramic views from the summit. The site is positioned approximately 750m to the W of the coastline.
Partial contour fort surrounding flat summit of steep mountain. Panoramic views from summit. Enclosing elements follow contours at NW - E and cuts across gently sloping ground at S.

Multiple enclosure surrounding the somewhat flat summit of Knocknashee, a steep, isolated mountain in low-lying terrain. The enclosing elements are positioned on the edge of an abrupt break of slope that marks the edge of this flat area. This topographical feature is very distinct and stands out in the landscape. Panoramic views from the summit.

Contour fort surrounding summit of domed hill at center of E - W running escarpment. Steep break of slope to E formed by the Linguan River and its valley has created a natural break in the escarpment. The hillfort overlooks this gap.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Hilltop on E - W running escarpment.

Landscape_Type_Comments: Surrounding summit of domed mountain at the N edge of the Silvermines Mountain range. Panoramic views from the summit. The hillfort overlooks a natural break in the mountains to the W and the Nenagh River to the S.

Multiple enclosure surrounding the summit and western facing slopes of Curraghadobbin Hill, at center of E - W running escarpment. Hillfort overlooks Brittas River to E, which has created a natural break in escarpment.
In commanding position surrounding domed summit of hilltop following natural contours of hill. Overlooking Moanamaddra Lough to E and Fishmoyne River to E and SE.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Hilltop at edge of mountainous terrain.

Landscape_Type_Comments: Contour fort on summit of steep sided hilltop. Positioned at the foothills of the E edge of the Galty Mountains with panoramic views from the summit.
Multiple enclosure following natural contours, surrounding S summit of isolated steep dome-shaped hill surrounded by low-lying terrain. Panoramic views from the summit.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Isolated steep dome-shaped hill with surrounding low-lying terrain.

Landscape_Type_Comments: Contour fort surrounding the summit of domed mountain at the N edge of the Silvermines Mountain range. Panoramic views from the summit. The hillfort overlooks a natural break in the mountains to the W.

Irregular shaped contour fort closely following the natural contours of Laghtea Hill. The enclosing elements are positioned surrounding a steep incline towards two summits. In commanding position overlooking the S fording point of Lough Derg and with panoramic views from the summit.
Multiple enclosure on low hilltop at E foothills of Silvermines Mountains, overlooking Cromoge River to E with panoramic views. Flat terrain to the N, E and S give particular emphasis to these views.

Circular contour fort surrounding summit of Ballybuckley Hill. Panoramic views from summit. Overlooked by Bree Hill 1.4km to W and Carrig Hill 0.9km to NW but with excellent views of the Slaney River to the NE, E and SE.
Contour fort positioned immediately E of the summit of a broad, low hill. Extensive views to the N, E and W. Overlooking the town of Raheen and Templeshelin Stream to N.

Surrounding the SE flat topped summit of Spinans Hill at SW edge of Wicklow mountains, with panoramic views. The outer enclosing elements of this large multiple enclosure is incorporated into the larger Spinans Hill 2 (Atlas No.0727) contour fort. Brusselstown Ring is one of nine hillforts comprising the Baltinglass hillfort cluster.

Partial contour fort surrounding the domed summit of steep hilltop. The enclosing elements follow the natural contours of the hill at the N and W. At the NE, the bank runs down slope and continues to the E across a gentle slope rather than utilizing the steeper slope uphill. The hilltop itself is prominent and sits at the E edge of the Wicklow mountains overlooking Greystones town and the Wicklow coastline.

Oval shaped partial contour fort surrounding the domed summit of Downshill. Steep slopes to N, E and S with gentler slopes to W (Grogan and Kilfeather 1997, 42). Hillfort rampart follows contours at N and W before running down slope at E and following a lower contour to the SW. In commanding position at edge of the Glen of the Downs and overlooking the Wicklow coastline to the E.

Hillslope fort positioned on sloping ground with steep break of slope to N, E and S. Hill gently rises to hill shoulder at the SW which is overlooked by hilltop with barrow at its summit. Hillfort overlooks modern copper mine 20m to SE and S and the Avoca valley to E. There are excellent views of this river valley from the hillfort.

Possible multiple enclosure positioned surrounding low-domed summit of hilltop. Fort follows contours of hill and takes advantage of steep break of slope to N. Large multiple enclosure overlooking hillfort 300m to S. Excellent views to N, E and W.

Circular multiple enclosure positioned surrounding the flat summit of hilltop at the end of a prominent east-west shoulder of upland  and overlooking tributary of Derreen River to immediate W (Raftery 1976, 339). The large multiple enclosure of Knockeen situated 300m to N. Rathgall is positioned on higher ground and overlooks Knockeen.

Multiple enclosure positioned on highest summit of Tuckmill Hill. Tuckmill Hill is a steep tripartite hilltop overlooking the modern town of Baltinglass to the SW. Two other hillforts are positioned on the N and W summit of the hill. Rathcoran hillfort follows the contours of the domed summit of the hill. There are panoramic views from the highest point within the interior. Rathcoran is one of nine hillforts comprising the Baltinglass hillfort cluster.

Multiple enclosure surrounding the N ridge of Tuckmill Hill, a steep tripartite hilltop overlooking the modern town of Baltinglass to the SW. Two other hillforts are positioned on the S and W summit of the hill. The hillfort does not follow the contours of the hill. The ramparts disregard topographical variation to form three circular enclosures. Rathnagree is one of nine hillforts comprising the Baltinglass hillfort cluster.

Contour fort located in commanding position on domed E summit of Spinans Hill at SW edge of Wicklow mountains. Panoramic views from the summit. The fort strictly follows the contours of the hill. Spinans Hill 1 is one of nine hillforts comprising the Baltinglass hillfort cluster.

Main_Display_Name: Spinans Hill 2, Wicklow (Brusselstown, Spinans Middle, Castlequater, Castlesallagh, Coolamaddra, Eadestown Hill, Moorstown, Spinans Hill, Ballyhubbock.)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Contour fort surrounding all of Spinans Hill and enclosing the hillforts of Brusselstown Ring (Atlas No.0718) and Spinans Hill 1 (Atlas No.0726) at SW edge of Wicklow mountains. The hillfort surrounds two summits. Spinans Hill 2 is one of nine hillforts comprising the Baltinglass hillfort cluster.

Multiple enclosure in commanding position surrounding domed summit of Tinoran Hill. This summit is located on the N edge of a N - S running hill ridge overlooking the River Slaney immediately to the E. Tinoran is one of nine hillforts comprising the Baltinglass hillfort cluster.

Univallate contour fort in commanding positioned on W ridge of Tuckmill Hill, a steep tripartite hilltop overlooking the modern town of Baltinglass to the SW. The hillfort is located on level terrain with a steep break of slope to the W. Overlooked by Rathcoran hillfort (Atlas No.0724) to E and Tinoran hillfort to SE.

Possible contour fort in commanding positioned surrounding the domed summit of Kilranlagh Hill at SW edge of Wicklow mountains. Panoramic views from the summit. Kilranlagh is one of nine hillforts that comprise the Baltinglass hillfort complex in Wicklow.

Bivallate contour fort in commanding position surrounding the domed summit of hilltop, overlooking tributary of River Clare to E. This hilltop is the highest point of a SE-NW running prominent ridge overlooking low-lying terrain in all directions. Panoramic views from the summit.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Hilltop on S edge of ridge.

Landscape_Type_Comments: Univallate hillslope fort surrounding the summit and S slopes of Knockacarrigeen Hill. Positioned in low-lying terrain, the hillfort has excellent view in all directions and particularily to the N, E and S. Knockma Hill overlooks the hilltop 1.5km to the W.

Coastal promontory fort positioned at edge of cliff face to SW, on the Aran Island of Inishmore, overlooking entrance to Galway Bay. Interior of hillfort is level, however, the site as a whole is positioned on land sloping to the E.
Univallate contour fort surrounding summit of domed, low-rise hilltop in low-lying terrain. Panoramic views from the summit.
Multiple enclosure surrounding the summit of domed hilltop of Kilskeagh Hill. There are panoramic views from the summit, with particulatily impressive views of low-lying terrain to the S and W.
Contour fort surrounding the domed summit of Gentian Hill, a prominent hilltop jutting out into Galway Bay. Panoramic views of Galway Bay within hillfort interior.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Gentian Hill jutting out into Galway Bay.

Landscape_Type_Comments: Multiple enclosure positioned on domed NW summit of a SW-NW running ridge, overlooking a number of small river tributaries to the W. Panoramic views from the summit. Enclosing elements are widely spaced and do not follow contours of the hill.

Large multiple enclosure surrounding the domed summit of Boley Hill, on the NE edge of the Castlecomber Hills. The hillfort overlooks the Douglas River to the S and commands the valley to the S and SW.

Possible multiple enclosure situated on top of high rock outcrop with panoramic views from the summit. The fort overlooks a prominent E-W gap through an extensive ridge of hills and the Crooked River to the S.

Univallate contour fort surrounding the domed summit of prominent hilltop. Panoramic views of the surrounding low-lying terrain from the summit, overlooking Ballinamore and Ballyconnell canal to NW and Dooloughan Lough immediately to the NE.

Positioned on a prominent hill at the S edge of upland terrain. The hillfort surrounds a flat plateau and is enclosed on all sides by a steep break of slope. Overlooking low-lying terrain to S (Kytmannow et al. 2010).

Main_Display_Name: The Ditches, North Cerney, Gloucestershire (Ditches Hillfort; Ditches)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Bivallate partial contour hillfort, now recognised only as cropmarks as ploughed out, located on SW-facing spur on the shoulder of the Great Oolite ridge at headwaters of River Churn in S Cotswolds.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Northern half of site nearly flat with southern part dropping slightly to a small spur on the shoulder of the Great Oolite ridge

Landscape_Type_Comments: Bivallate and rectangular in plan, strongly defended partial contour hillfort sited on top of low ridge in gently undulating farmland above brooks to E and W (Ampney Brook), S of Cotswolds.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located on top of low ridge rising above undulating farmland

Landscape_Type_Comments: Sub-rectangular, univallate, inland promontory fort located on W Cotswold scarp edge above streams running to River Isbourne on W and River Windrush on E.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located on westerly slopes above a steep re-entrant valley

Landscape_Type_Comments: Univallate, partial contour hillfort located on W-facing Inferior Oolite ridge of N Cotswolds, W of Rood Gate, at headwaters of River Isbourne to W and River Windrush to E.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Not strong site but on ridge top generally level with surrounding landat the headwaters of Beesmoor Brook

Landscape_Type_Comments: Univallate, partial contour fort located in commanding position on NNW-facing spur on plateau edge above sharp bend in River Coln immediately to N in S Cotswolds. Surrounding slopes steep and wooded (Ablington Grove) to N, steep to E and moderate to S and W on scarp plateau.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located on a sharp bend of the River Coln next to the river

Landscape_Type_Comments: Large univallate partial contour hillfort sited on spur of Great Oolite at confluence of River Leach and a tributary above shallow valley in S Cotswolds.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located on a slight spur at the confluence of the River Leach and a tributary

Landscape_Type_Comments: Important, excavated promontory fort located on a W-facing Cotswold spur overlooking vale and Gloucester to E. Very steep surrounding slopes on N, W and S, moderate along ridge to E.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located on a western facing Cotswold spur

Main_Display_Name: The Castles, Dowdeswell, Gloucestershire (Castle Barn Farm)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Slight sub-rectangular, univallate, partial contour hillfort located on NW-facing spur above bend of River Chelt in S Cotswolds.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located on a north-west facing spur above the valley of the River Chelt

Landscape_Type_Comments: Partial contour hillfort located on SE-facing spur above confluence of River Churn and Hilcot Brook to SE in S Cotswolds. Slightly sloping to SE.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located on a south-east hillslope spur dominating the confluence of the River Churn and Hilcot Brook

Landscape_Type_Comments: Possible large contour hillfort, much affected by the present Stow-on-the-Wold development, situated on top of hill immediately to NE of Stow-on-the-Wold.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Sited on the tip of a Cotswold spur above the River Dikler to the west and River Evenlode to the east

Main_Display_Name: Uley Bury Camp, Gloucestershire (Uleybury; Uley Bury)

Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located on steep natural slopes, the defences possibly scarped

Landscape_Type_Comments: Large, roughly rectangular, multivallate promontory hillfort located between steep re-entant valleys above River Leach to W and Sherborne Brook to E, W of village of Farmington.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located at the headwaters of the Sherborne Brook, a tributary of the River Windrush between re-entrant valleys

Landscape_Type_Comments: Univallate, nearly circular, contour hillfort located on the highest point in the area above River Leach to W on the S Cotswold scarp.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located on Cotswold downland above the River Windrush to the north-east

Landscape_Type_Comments: Large partial contour , part bivallate, hillfort located on N-facing Cotswold spur of Willersey Hill
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Escarpment of hill gives steep natural defence to the north

Landscape_Type_Comments: Bivallate part marsh and part level terrain fort, enclosing c. 23ha located on virtual flat ground in open valley on gravel terrace in angle between the Rivers Windrush and Dikler and confluence of the River Dilker and River Eye, immediately to E of Bouton-on-Water.

Landscape_Type_Comments: Formerly circular univallate partial contour hillfort located on NE-facing spur of Cotswold escarpment above streams flowing into River Evenlode on E and streams flowing into River Dikler to W.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Sited on east facing slopes on Icomb Hill, prominent above the River Evenlode valley

Landscape_Type_Comments: Inland promontory hillfort located on prominent NW-facing Cotswold spur of Nottingham Hill.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located on the prominent Nottingham Hill above the Vale of Gloucester and opposite to Cleeve Cloud

Landscape_Type_Comments: Bivallate hill-fort located on p[lateau-edge of Cleeve Cloud enclosing c. 1.2ha. Ramparts formed by two series of bank and outer ditch, enclosing slight promontory of gently sloping ground to their SW, extending for c. 100m up to partly quarried scarp edge of Inferior Oolite above Cheltenham.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located on the ridge of Cleeve Cloud at 300m, the land sloping to the west to the steep quarry edge

Landscape_Topography_Comments: Typical western Cotswolds location at the end of a spur on Haresfield Beacon

Landscape_Type_Comments: Univallate contour hillfort located on a low NW-facing spur, at 50m O.D. just above the River Severn floodplain to W.
Bivallate contour fort located on a low SW-facing spur on the edge of a shallow valley, just N of Thames Head, source of the River Thames. River Frome to NW.

Landscape_Type_Comments: Complex, multivallate, partial contour hillfort located on N part of a narrow spur overlooking Flaxley Valley on E edge of Forest of Dean where few hillforts.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located on a narrow spur overlooking the Flaxley Valley on the eastern edge of the Forest of Dean where few hillforts are located. The site is very steep on the east and northern sides, gentler on the south and west

Landscape_Type_Comments: Bivallate hillslope hillfort located on NW-facing slope of prominent spur of Cotswold escarpment (Shenberrow Hill), above Vale of Evesham to W.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located on a sloping spur of the Cotswold escarpment

Landscape_Type_Comments: Univallate promontory fort located on W-facing spur of Cotswold escarpment overlooking the Vale of Evesham.
Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located on a spur of the Cotwold escarpment

Landscape_Topography_Comments: Located obn a Cotswold spur

A partial contour fort that encloses the N end of an isolated flat-topped hill

A hillslope fort on a gentle slope overlooking the Nene Valley, aspect E.

Landscape_Type_Comments: On the S slopes of a small valley, a tributary of the River Nene.
A partial contour fort on a plateau top, overlooking the Cherwell Valley to the W.

Landscape_Type_Comments: A hillslope for overlooking the Cherwell Valley, aspect E.
Possible contour fort on a hill top
Follows the contours around the top of an isolated, flat-topped, steep-sided hill.
A partial contour fort on the top of a ridge with steep slopes to the N and S.

Landscape_Type_Comments: A partial contour fort on an isolated ridge top with good views to N and S
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: On a ridge top with good views to N and S

Landscape_Type_Comments: On hillslope facing E

Main_Display_Name: Camp Hill, Dumfries & Galloway (Enrig Camp, Camp Hill Enrick)

Landscape_Type_Comments: Univallate contour fort in commanding position on domed summit of Forkill Mountain with panoramic views from the summit and overlooking the modern town of Forkill to the immediate W.

Main_Display_Name: Doon Castle, Ardwell Point, Dumfries & Galloway

Landscape_Type_Comments: Possible multiple enclosure surrounding domed summit of hillock. Panoramic views from summit, overlooking Curran Lough to the immediate SE and the Oona Water, a tributary of the Black Water River to the W.
Positioned at the W edge of a ridge of hills, univallate contour fort surrounds the slightly domed summit of hill with excellent views in all directions. Overlooking Lough Neagh to W and NW.
Multiple enclosure in commanding position surrounding the domed summit of Lisbanoe hill. Panoramic views from summit, overlooking Callan River and Butler River to immediate E.
Character uncertain
Univallate contour fort surrounding the low domed summit of hilltop at E interface of mountainous terrain and low-lying agricultural land. Extensive views to the N, E and S.
Univallate contour fort on domed summit of isolated hilltop overlooking low-lying terrain in all directions. Panoramic views from the summit.

Large Multiple enclosure surrounding the domed summit of hilltop. Positioned in commanding location at edge of upland terrain, overlooking the Broadford River and Glenomra River and an important mountain pass running E-W through the Slieve Bernagh Mountains.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Hilltop at edge of upland terrain.

Landscape_Type_Comments: Large multiple enclosure in commanding position in hilltop in low-lying terrain and overlooking the Shannon Estuary to the S and W. Panoramic views from the summit..
Contour fort on summit of Doon Hill, positioned at the NE of a hill ridge. Overlooking the modern village of Kilfenora and a number of tributaries of the Dealagh River to the N, NE and NW.

Main_Display_Name: Grianán of Aileach, Donegal (Greenan Mountain, Carrowreagh, Toulett, Speenoge)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Multiple enclosure in commanding position at domed summit of Greenan Mountain, overlooking Lough Swilly. Panoramic views from the summit.
Large contour fort surrounding the domed summit of Lurgan Hill at W edge of upland terrain, overlooking low-lying terrain and Donegal coastline to the W.

Pear shaped partial contour fort surrounding the domed summit of Lyles Hill. Panoramic views from the summit, with particularly impressive views of low lying land to the N. The enclosing elements follow the contours of the hill from NW-SE and cut across the slope at the S and SW in particular.

Knockdhu hillfort is a large multivallate inland promontory fort. The monument uses cliff edges on the N, E and SE as a natural barrier. The western approach is protected using a series of three bank and ditch earthworks. The natural promontory is an impressive and commanding feature in the landscape and affords panoramic views, with particularly impressive views of the Antim coastline and the Irish sea to the E.

Main_Display_Name: Lurigethan, Antrim (Foriff, Knockans North, Knockans South, Red Bay, Cortaleean)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Lurigethan hillfort is a large multivallate inland promontory fort. The monument uses cliff edges to the NW, NE and SE as a natural barrier. The SW approach is protected using a series of up to six banks and ditches. The natural promontory is an impressive and commanding feature in the landscape and affords panoramic views, with particularly impressive views of the Antim coastline and the Irish sea to the E.
Partial contour fort surrounding the flat-topped summit and E facing slopes of Dunmill Hill with extensive views to the N, E and S.

Partial contour fort surrounding the summit of hilltop, overlooking Coppony Lough and tributaries of the Annalee River. Extensive views of low-lying terrain to the S. The N section of the enclosing elements run across the slope of the hill. The remainder of the defences follow the contours of the hill.
Contour fort located in commanding position surrounding summit of Downpatrick Hill, with panoramic views from the summit.
Multiple enclosure surrounding summit at the NE end of a hill ridge overlooking the Derg river valley to N. Panoramic views from the summit.
Univallate contour fort surrounding the domed summit of Mallabeny Hill an isolated hilltop overlooking wide valley to S. Panoramic views from the summit.
Univallate contour fort surrounding the upper part of a steep drumlin (Warner 2009, 510). Panoramic views from the summit. A particular emphasis on views of the wide valley to the N.

Partial contour fort surrounding the summit of Tycanny Hill with panoramic views from the summit and particularly good views of the N, E and S. The enclosing elements roughly follow the contours of the hilltop and the N, E and W, but run across the natural slope at the W.

Contour fort positioned at the summit of hilltop, overlooking a bend in Ballycotton River to NE, E and SE and tributaries of Ballysteen River to W. Panoramic views from summit with excellent views of Liscannor Bay to S.
Level terrain fort positioned at edge of slight ridge with excellent views to the N, E and W.
Hillslope fort positioned on a slight natural ridge with excellent views to the NE, E, SE, and S. The fort also overlooks the Owenogarney River to the immediate E.
Small multiple enclosure positioned E facing sloping ground with excellent views to NW to SE.
Fort abutting the E side of Ballycar Lough flood plain. Excellent views to the NE, E and SE.
Hillslope fort positioned at the SE slopes of hilltop. Located on gently sloping ground with steep break of slope to the immediate E and S.
Level terrain fort overlooking the modern town of Shannon to the immediate SW. Extensive views of the Shannon River to the S.
Oval level terrain fort positioned on gently sloping ground, overlooking Skeheen Lough and Town Lough to the E and SE. Extensive views of the S and E from interior.
Small pear-shaped contour fort surrounding the flat summit of hilltop and overlooking Owenogarney River to E. In low-lying land with extensive views to the E and S.

The promontory is located on a level area on the edge of a sheer cliff composed of vertical shales with veins of slate and mud stone. It is located at an altitude of 24m OD and enclosed by a high bank and deeply cut external ditch representing a well-defined convex curve to the land.

The fort is located on a slight S-facing slope at an altitude of 6m OD. It is a small sub-rectangular area projecting S into the Atlantic; connected to the mainland by a narrow neck of land. The only access to the promontory is through this narrow approach, averaging about 1.5m wide. On the N side there is a vertical drop of 15m while the S side is less severe. All along the N side of the fort the cliff is vertical and 18m high and this applies also to the section on the E side.
The fort is located on a slight SW-facing slope at an altitude of 10m OD. It is a small area of land of c. 0.02ha enclosed by an earthen bank and an external ditch.

Main_Display_Name: Baile Iarthach Thuaidh (Ballyieragh North), Cork (Cape Clear) (Doonthomas)
Landscape_Type_Comments: The site is situated on a rapidly eroding headland that projects SW from Cape Clear Island off the SW coast of Co. Cork.
The promontory is a level, sub-rectangular area of land at 4m OD that projects W into Roaringwater Bay from Sherkin Island in West Cork.
The promontory is a rectangular area at an altitude of 12m OD that projects NE into Ballydonegan Bay. The interior slopes down steeply to N and S.
The promontory is an oval area at an altitude of 12m OD that projects N into Ballydonegan Bay. The interior slopes down steeply to N and S.

The promontory is a small irregular area at an altitude of 4m OD that projects W into Dunmanus Bay. The fort commands an extensive view across the Blairs Cove and down Dunmanus Bay. The eroding defences consist of a large curving bank and external ditch and are overgrown. The interior has been eroded quite considerably in the last century.

The fort is located on the low shore of Fox's Cove in an area consisting of grassy drift banks on low rocks to the W of Courtmacsherry Bay. It is situated at an altitude of 10m OD projecting SW from the mainland and defended by a large bank and external ditch.
Triangular headland projecting SW into Clonakilty Bay adjacent to Barry's Cove at an altitude of 9m OD. Defended on the E side by a single earthen bank.

The triangular area of land projects E into Dunmanus Bay, defended on the W side by a curving bank and external ditch. It is situated at an altitude of 23m OD near Foillmore cliff, a number of low peninsulas with little headlands and creeks.

The fort can be described as a small rectangular mound with an external fosse on a low headland barley projecting W into Bantry Bay. It is situated at an altitude of 6m OD  with views of Whiddy Island to the N.

The fort can be described as a small oval area defended by an earthen bank and an external ditch projecting N into Dunmanus Bay. It is situated at an altitude of 8m OD with views of the the Sheep's Head peninsula to the N.

The site occupies a remote and somewhat inaccessible nook among low hills to the N of the Ivagha peninsula. It is located at the westernmost point of Mizen peninsula, on S side of the Three Castles Head and Dun Lough at an altitude of 62m OD. There are extensive views of the great rock islands of Caher, Illaunacaheragh and Illaunbirrane. Only traces of the fort survive today in front of, and on same line as, the curtain wall of Late Medieval defences (CO146-001002-). These run  for 25m from cliff to S at Coosnaronety Cove.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: The site is overlooked by a series of hills to the N

Landscape_Type_Comments: The site is situated on a narrow, E-sloping spur overlooking Dunnycove strand and a number of smaller bays. At an Altitude of 23m OD, it falls precipitously to a lower rock platform, to the south of which runs a small creek, with parallel sides. The original promontory was defended by a single rock-cut ditch which ran in front of the Medieval castle.

The fort can be described as a rectangular area projecting SW into the Atlantic at an altitude of 9m OD. Seaward end of promontory slopes down steeply to W to exposed, eroding rock. There is a sheer drop on the E side.

Main_Display_Name: Double Dykes, Sodom Hill, South Lanarkshire

Landscape_Type_Comments: Possible multiple enclosure site, originally a stone-built contour hillfort, located on the summit of hill on Tonkins Downs. Moderate to steep surrounding slopes, less so on broad ridge to NW, W and S.
The promontory can be described as a rectangular area projecting W into Dunworley Bay at an altitude of 5m OD.

The promontory is situated on the E side of Sherkin Island on the SW coast of Co. Cork at an altitude of 11m OD. The headland slopes gently E into Baltimore Harbour. The promontory is occupied by the remains of late medieval fortifications (CO149-018002).

The promontory can be described as a roughly triangular area of 2.18ha that projects E into Atlantic at an altitude of 25m OD. The headland slopes gradually to the E and has extensive views from Castlehaven to the Squince and on to Dundeady and Galley Head.

Main_Display_Name: Range Castle, Dumfries & Galloway (Rangecastle Hill; Holmains)

Landscape_Type_Comments: The headland, which can be described as an irregular area projecting N into Bantry Bay, is isolated from mainland by a natural sea arch (Wth 5.4m).
This promontory is located on the S side of Bear Island at Doonbeg Head off the SW coast of Co. Cork. The headland projects SW from the Island into Bantry Bay at an altitude of 80m OD

The promontory has extensive views of the Beara peninsula to the N and can be described as a small, almost level rectangular area projecting SW from slightly larger headland which projects N into Bantry Bay at an altitude of 6m OD.

Irregular headland projects N into Dunmanus Bay. Described by Westropp as a 'rocky peninsula with low cliffs over which huge waves break in western gales' (1915, 277). The headland is defended at neck by two banks.

Main_Display_Name: Gars Hill, West Roucan, Dumfries & Galloway
Lissamona/Lios Ó Móine (Clear Island), Cork (Clear Island) (Port)
Landscape_Type_Comments: The promontory is situated at Stuckaunaminnaun Cove, on the N side of Clear Island on the SW coast of Co. Cork. The headland is a trapezoidal area  projecting N from Cape Clear at an altitude of 11m OD.
The headland can be defined as a small rectangular area projecting SW into Castlehaven Bay at an altitude of 11m OD. It slopes gently from E to W.
The headland can be defined as a small rectangular  area projecting SE over Siege Cove at an altitude of 25m OD.
It can be defined as a low rocky island  (named 'Doonlea' on both eds OS 6-inch map) separated by narrow gorge from sloping promontory on N shore of Ballydivlin Bay.

Main_Display_Name: Ballyieragh North (Clear Island), Cork (Clear Island) (Baile Iarthach Thuaidh, Dunanore)
Landscape_Type_Comments: The promontory is situated on the NW side of Cape Clear off the SW coast of Co. Cork. The rectangular area of land projects W between two coves; Tonelunga and Coosadoona at an altitude of 9m OD
Sub-rectangular area of approximately 0.43ha that projects NE into Garinish Bay. Regarded by Westropp (1921a, 7) as suitable location for promontory fort.

Main_Display_Name: Calf Island East, Cork (Calf Island East) (Dooneen Island)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Rectangular rocky island on NW side of Calf Island situated at an altitude of 4m OD.
Insufficient information to be included as a type of fort
Small irregular area of approximately 0.58ha that projects SW into the Altantic at an altitude of 39m OD. No indication of fort defences.
It can be described as a low rocky promontory on E side Toormore Bay at an elevation of 8m OD. No visible trace of defences earlier than the tower-house on promontory.
A promontory beyond a narrow neck of land projecting SW into Rosscarbery Bay at an altitude of 4m OD.
A possible promontory fort on small island projecting SE into Castle Bay at an altitude of 9m OD.

Main_Display_Name: Arberry Hill, Northamptonshire (Arbury Hill; Thenford Hill Camp)
Landscape_Type_Comments: Hillslope fort on S facing slope of a prominent hill
Irregular coastal promontory projecting S into the Atlantic at an altitude of 30m OD.
Promontory can be described as a short headland on S coast of the Beara Peninsula projecting S into the Atlantic.
Oval promontory, sloping to the NW in an isolated position on the N shore of Kilcatherine Headland. It is linked to the mainland by a narrow sea-arch at an altitude of 3m OD.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: The site is overlooked to the S by a series of sheer cliffs at an altitude of 18m OD.

Landscape_Type_Comments: Defined as a sub-rectangular area of approximately 1.48ha that projects SE into Newfoundland Bay. The promontory is defined on the landward side by an earthen bank with external ditch at an altitude of 11m OD.

Main_Display_Name: Park Hill, Hillhead, Dumfries & Galloway (Parks; Parkhill)

Landscape_Type_Comments: Coastal promontory composed of an irregular landmass of approximately 0.99ha, projecting SE into Atlantic. It is connected to the mainland by a narrow neck.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: It is overlooked to the N by a series of low hills.

Landscape_Type_Comments: Coastal promontory can be described as a rectangular headland of approximately 0.71ha that projects S into the sea at an altitude of 9m OD. The neck is defended by three earthen banks (H 1 -2.5m) and three ditches.

situated in rough pasture, on a promontory projecting E, with high cliffs on three sides, and with views S to High Island and Low Island. Near its W end, the promontory is defended by the remains of an earthen bank and external ditch.
A roughly rectangular area , with high cliffs on three sides, projects SW into Bantry Bay. The remains of an ENE-WSW linear stone wall extends across the level neck of the promontory
Rocky promontory, jutting W into the sea, with tall cliffs on its S, W and N sides
Promontory can be described as an irregular landmass that projects W into the sea at an altitude of 10m OD, with extensive views of the Berra peninsula.

The headland can be described as a small irregular area that projects SW into the Atlantic. The neck of the promontory is crossed by a natural rock spine above a fault plane 3.25m in depth. Two other natural rock faults running parallel to each other are recorded on the headland, which has an altitude of 9m OD.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Site is overlooked by headland to the E

Landscape_Type_Comments: Headland can be described as an elongated stack barely projecting into the sea to the SW. It is bounded by a tumble of large rocks to the SE and NE and by the sea to the NW and SW and is situated at an altitude of 3m OD.
Landscape_Topography_Dominant: Headland is overlooked by ridge to the S

Landscape_Type_Comments: Promontory can be described as a tower-like platform barely projecting S from the mainland with almost perpendicular sides, and revetted with good masonry.
